showStyleConfigManifest.name: GFX Templates
showStyleConfigManifest.description: This table can contain info in two ways. Things marked (**) are always required. If you want to do the mapping from iNews-code, then all (*)-elements are aslo required. VizTemplate is what the graphic is called in viz. Source layer is the ID of the Sofie Source layer in the UI (i.e. "studio0_graphicsTema"). Layer mapping is the Sofie studio layer mapping (i.e "viz_layer_tema").  iNews command can be something like "KG=", then iNews Name is the thing that follows in iNes i.e. "ident_nyhederne"

columns.name: iNews Command (*)
columns.description: The code as it will appear in iNews

columns.name: iNews Name (*)
columns.description: The name after the code

columns.name: Viz Template Name (**)
columns.description: The name of the Viz Template

columns.name: Graphic Engine Destination (*)
columns.description: The name of the graphics engine to play this graphic on

columns.name: Out type
columns.description: The type of out, none follow timecode, S stays on to ??, B stays on to ??, O stays on to ??

columns.name: Changes Design
columns.description: Whether this cue changes the design

columns.name: Source layer (**)
columns.description: The ID of the source layer to place the piece on in Sofie UI

columns.name: Layer mapping (**)
columns.description: The Sofie Layer mapping to use in playback. This will ensure proper viz transition logic by matching the viz layers.

columns.name: Effekt Number
columns.description: The Effect Number

columns.name: Clip Name
columns.description: The name of the wipe clip

columns.name: Effekt Duration
columns.description: Duration of the effekt

columns.name: Alpha at Start
columns.description: Number of frames of alpha at start

columns.name: Alpha at End
columns.description: Number of frames of alpha at end

showStyleConfigManifest.name: Breaker Configuration
showStyleConfigManifest.description: Clip name is the clip name without file extension. Duration is the length of the file, including trailing audio. Alpha start is the number of frames from the first frame and until the jingle covers the full frame. The alpha end is how many frames from the alpha starts fading out, until the very end of the file.
